‘No lordly pile or fortune great is mine, but a kind poetic gilla little farm, are all that Ι possess. 'Tis quite enough for me. But you though life is insecure, still build your palaces and grudge the very sea its shore3 you drive your poor clients from their homes that yur may satisfy your greed for land. Your sure home is the halis of Death:¹ Earth's doors open for rich and poor alike. No bribes move the grin ferryman.'

This ode handles again Horace's favorite theme—the vanityof riches and ambition the wisdom of the golden mean. The same senti ments are expressed 1, 313 2, 163 3, 1, 40-48. 24. 1 ff. As frequently elsewhere he takes his own case as an illustration 01 the ideal lot,iu which man is content with his moderate estate, and contrasts it with that of the rich man whose greed defles the sacred laws of nature and of man. Horace has no individual in mind, but with his fondness for concrete statement gives his verses a dramatic turn by the direct forn of address.
